  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem is broken down into checking the existence of a power of 2 (k(n)=1) and then checking for k(n)=2 and k(n)=3 using modular arithmetic and properties of 2023.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "helper_1",
      "instructions": "Determine if there exists an integer n such that 2023*n is a power of 2. If not, explain why based on the prime factorization of 2023."
    },
    {
      "label": "helper_2",
      "instructions": "Test the possibility of k(n)=2. This requires checking if 2023 divides 2^a + 2^b for some integers a, b. Specifically, check if 2023 divides 2^m + 1 for some m. Use the fact that 2023 is divisible by 7 to check if 2^m + 1 is ever 0 mod 7. If k(n)=2 is impossible, investigate if k(n)=3 is possible."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "The parent should combine the results to determine the minimum k(n). If helper_1 shows k(n)=1 is impossible and helper_2 shows k(n)=2 is impossible, the answer is the smallest k(n) found (likely 3) that satisfies the condition."
}

